        "value": 200,
        "unit": "W",
        "description": "Typical range for industrial cleaning of cast iron to remove rust or contaminants without substrate damage; starting at 200W balances efficiency and safety. Max limited to avoid melting (cast iron melting point ~1150-1300°C). Source: IPG Photonics laser cleaning systems specs for metal surfaces; academic review in Optics and Lasers in Engineering (2018)."
      },
      "scan_speed": {
        "min": 10,
        "max": 5000,
        "value": 2000,
        "unit": "mm/s",
        "description": "Effective range for 1064 nm cleaning on cast iron; slower for heavy contamination (e.g., thick rust) to ensure ablation, faster for light oils. Recommended 2000 mm/s for optimal throughput with minimal heat input, considering cast iron's high thermal conductivity (~50 W/m·K). Source: Industry standards from Laserax equipment manuals; case studies in Journal of Cleaner Production (2020)."
      },
      "pulse_width": {
        "min": 0.1,
        "max": 1000,
        "unit": "ns",
        "value": 50,
        "description": "Nanosecond regime dominant for industrial cleaning of cast iron to achieve plasma-induced ablation with low heat-affected zone (HAZ); picosecond (ps) or femtosecond (fs) for ultra-precise but costlier applications. 50 ns recommended to minimize thermal diffusion in cast iron (reflectivity ~40% at 1064 nm). Source: Laser physics research in Applied Surface Science (2019); avoids fs due to overkill for contamination removal."
      },
      "repetition_rate": {
        "min": 1,
        "max": 200,
        "value": 100,
        "unit": "kHz",
        "description": "Standard range for pulsed fiber lasers in metal cleaning; 100 kHz balances cleaning speed and heat accumulation on cast iron, where high rates (>150 kHz) risk subsurface heating despite good conductivity. Trade-off: higher freq accelerates process but increases cumulative fluence. Source: Academic literature in Lasers in Manufacturing and Materials Processing (2021)."
      },
      "energy_density": {
        "min": 0.1,
        "max": 20,
        "value": 1.5,
        "unit": "J/cm²",
        "description": "Fluence range for safe removal of contaminants like rust or paint on cast iron; damage threshold ~2-4 J/cm² to avoid pitting or melting. 1.5 J/cm² recommended for effective cleaning below ablation threshold of cast iron (~3 J/cm² at 1064 nm). Conservative due to cast iron's variable surface roughness. Source: Ablation threshold studies in Journal of Applied Physics (2017); SPIE proceedings on laser cleaning."
      },
      "spot_size": {
        "min": 0.1,
        "max": 500,
        "unit": "μm",
        "value": 200,
        "description": "Beam diameter range for industrial scanners; smaller for fine details (e.g., crevices in castings), larger for broad areas. 200 μm recommended for uniform coverage on rough cast iron surfaces without excessive overlap heating. Source: Equipment specifications from Coherent and Trumpf laser systems; process optimization in Surface and Coatings Technology (2022)."
      },
      "pass_count": {
        "min": 1,
        "max": 10,
        "value": 2,
        "unit": "passes",
        "description": "Typically 1-3 passes for light to moderate contamination on cast iron; multi-pass for layered buildup (e.g., old paint). 2 passes recommended for complete removal while minimizing total energy input and HAZ. Single pass viable for thin rust. Source: Industry practice from case studies in International Journal of Advanced Manufacturing Technology (2019); manufacturer guidelines."
      },
